Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The number of countries and territories reporting confirmed of COVID-19 to WHO remains at 215. In the 24 hours since the last WHO update:

- The Americas region reported 47.1% of the global newly reported and 59.5% of newly reported for this 24-hour period, maintaining its dominance as the most severely affected region, having reported more than 10.6 million. The USA reported 39.4% of (39 894), followed by Brazil 21.8% (22 048), Colombia 10.0% (10 142), Argentina 7.3% (7369), Mexico 5.5% (5558), Peru 5.0% (5109), and Chile 1.5% (1572).

- The European region reported 11.1% of the global newly reported and 7.3% of the newly confirmed globally. Russia reported 21.3% (5102) of the regional newly confirmed, followed by Kazakhstan 8.8% (2114), Israel 7.3% (1756), Ukraine 6.0% (1443), Spain 5.9% (1418), France 5.4% (1293), Germany 5.1% (1226), Romania 5.1% (1215), Turkey 4.9% (1183), UK 4.8% (1148), the Netherlands 3.3% (779), Uzbekistan 2.8% (670) and Poland 2.3% (551).

- The Eastern Mediterranean region reported 5.7% of the global newly reported and 8.5% of global newly reported fatalities. Iraq reported 27.5% (3396) of the regional newly reported, followed by Iran 19.0% (2345), Saudi Arabia 12.3% (1521), Morocco 9.2% (1132), Pakistan 5.9% (730), Kuwait 5.6% (687), Palestinian Authority 3.8% (473), Bahrain 3.3% (407), Qatar 3.1% (384), Lebanon 2.5% (309), and Libya 0.10% (12). Cases are continuing to increase in Iraq and Morocco. This region remains highly active, with multiple countries still in a surge mode.

- The African region reported 2.9% of the global newly reported and 4.4% of newly reported fatalities. South Africa reported 39.7% (2511) of the newly reported in the region in the past 24 hours, followed by Ethiopia 9.2% (584), Kenya 7.8% (497), Algeria 7.7% (492), Nigeria 6.7% (423), and Ghana 3.0% (192).

- The Western Pacific region reported 2.2% of the global newly reported and 1.0% of global. The Philippines reported 60.8% (2900) of the newly reported in the region, followed by Japan 26.9% (1282), Australia 6.6% (316), Singapore 1.3% (61), China 1.3% (61), and South Korea 1.1% (54). The Philippines, Japan, and Australia continue to have elevated transmission.

- The South East Asia region reported 30.9% of the global newly reported and 19.2% of global. India reported 91.8% (60 963) of newly reported in the region, followed by Bangladesh 4.5% (2996) and Indonesia 2.5% (1693). India continues to be the driving force of the dominance of this region.

Impression: The overall picture is basically the same, even with residual weekend reporting artifact. The ordering of the regions has the Americas having the highest disease load and newly confirmed on a daily basis followed by the South East Asia region, then Europe followed by the Eastern Mediterranean, followed by the Africa region, and the Western Pacific region representing the lowest daily caseload of all the regions. While regional proportions may not reflect this, most of the regions have countries that have resurgences of associated with lifting of restrictions.

Figure 2. The epidemic curve of confirmed COVID-19 cases by date of report and WHO region, 30 Dec 2019 through 12 Aug 2020, at the source URL above is an excellent visual representation of the epidemic as described in the text above. - Mod.UBA]

