--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[The USA, Brazil, and India are still the most severely affected countries in terms of cumulative case counts. In the past 24 hours, these 3 countries -- India (67 066), followed by Brazil (58 081), and USA (54 345) -- account for over half of all confirmed globally (52.4%). There were 6821 deaths reported in the past 24 hours.

In descending rank order, India is number one for the number of newly confirmed in the past 24 hours, followed by Brazil, USA, Colombia, Peru, Argentina, Mexico, Russia, Philippines, and Iraq. The range in the top 10 daily newly confirmed goes from 3441 to 67 066. Other hotspots are seen in the countries numbered 11-20 in this list: Spain, Bangladesh, South Africa, France, Iran, Indonesia, Bolivia, Israel, and Chile; their range of reported new cases is 1552 to 3172. - Mod.UBA

Comparing the 7-day averages of daily confirmed cases from the past 7 days and those from 8-14 days ago, there is minimal change change (an increase of 1.2%,) and looking at daily reported deaths, the change is virtually not changed (increased by 0.75%). The key question still remains as to whether transmission is in fact slowing down or whether this is a reporting artifact. Time will tell, but following the data reports showing major surges in countries that had been showing successes makes one wonder what is driving these reporting variances (I haven't changed my mind!).

Impression: The SARS-CoV-2 is still actively being transmitted in all regions of the world, and many countries are showing increases in their daily newly confirmed case counts and mortality, while the global 7-day averages seem to reflect a slowing down of reporting confirmed; albeit, I still wonder whether this is real or reflects a changing pattern with decreased testing. For example, the USA reported data suggests a slowing down of transmission over the past 2 weeks as seen by the comparative 7-day averages in reported new and (see section [3E] above), but if one looks at the percentage of positive PCR tests, in the past 2 weeks the positivity rate is stable at 9%, consistent with significant ongoing transmission that is not abating (see https://www.cdc.gov/coronavirus/2019-ncov/cases-updates/testing-in-us.html). The most severely affected region is the Americas, with increasing daily, even though the comparative 7-day average suggests things may be slowing down (or reporting is slowing down). - Mods.UBA/MPP]
